% argument and main findings
Building on the fiscal sociology paradigm,\footnote{For an excellent overview of both classic and new fiscal sociology refer to \citet[Ch. 1]{Martin2009a}.} I argue that when the implementation of the income tax reflected the \emph{early foundational sectoral cleavage}, an important feature according to the fiscal sociology, this institution contributed to form the Latin American state (see \autoref{causal:mechanism:fig}). Analytically, I consider sectoral conflicts the trigger of both fiscal expansion and state development. Economic sectors not only shaped the economic landscape. Given that each sector has a corresponding political arm, the \emph{sectoral economic} conflict was also a \emph{political} conflict.\footnote{See \citet{Ansell:2014ty}.} Elsewhere I find that in high capacity states the income tax was product of an inter-sectoral conflict between the agricultural and industrial elites.\footnote{\citet{Bahamonde:2017ac}.} While weaker Latin American states would eventually implement the income tax law as well, this institution crystallized the leading role of the landowning class, not the profound restructuring of the post-colonial institutional order. This is relevant since the landed Latin American elites were an economic hegemonic group protected by norms and institutions that originated in colonial times. While the agricultural sector dominated most of the economy, the landowning class controlled most of the politics.\footnote{See for the Chilean case \citet[13]{Zeitlin:1984aa}, \citet[45]{Bauer:2008kx}, \citet[1748]{Baland2008} and \citet[56]{Best1976}, \citet{Rippy:1971rz}, \citet{Marichal:1989bh}.} However, the structural transformation characterized by ``a secular decline of agriculture and substantial expansion of manufacturing''\footnote{\citet[567]{Johnston1961}.} imposed tight constraints on the way politics was run by the incumbent landowning class.\footnote{\citet{Bahamonde:2017ab}.} Given the initial advantage of the landed elites, the secular emergence of the industrial sector meant the reduction of inter-sectoral inequality, positing political, economic and military threats to the landed elites.\footnote{\citet{Boix:2015aa}. For example, elites could use a faction of the existing army or hire private militias.} In turn, the lack of an economic challenger prevented political contestation and further institutional investments. Consequently, low inter-sectoral inequality made possible higher levels of inter-sectoral contestation giving way to a series of inter-elite compromises. In this paper I identify one such compromise, the implementation of the income tax. The Chilean case shows that industrial elites accepted to be income taxed in exchange of being allowed to participate in politics under fairer conditions. In turn, the implementation of the income tax expanded the \emph{dominion} of the state via bureaucratic development and accumulation of know-how.\footnote{\citet{Bahamonde:2017ac}.} Critically, the \emph{praxis} of converting private income into public property gave the \emph{tax state} the capacity to enforce other institutions throughout the territory. In this paper I identify one such institution, building codes. 


Exploiting the randomness of earthquake shocks, I leverage a novel historical dataset on Chilean earthquake death tolls and a Bayesian multilevel Poisson model to account for state capacities \emph{at the local level} between 1900 and 2010. I contend that the capacity the state has of enforcing and monitoring building codes throughout the territory is a \emph{reflexion} of its \emph{overall} state capacities. Earthquakes death-tolls are orthogonal to regime type, economic development and geography. Thus, keeping magnitudes constant, (weighted) death toll differentials should be attributable to the capacities the state has of enforcing these norms throughout the real only. Critically, these capacities are not a nationally uniform process, but a territorially heterogeneous one. \citet[1359]{ODonnell1993} famously distinguished different levels of state penetration, where \emph{in the same country} there were `brown areas,' or heterogeneous areas that mixed both `high' and `low' levels of stateness. Following this distinction (and \citet[]{Soifer2008a} in particular), I claim that the capacity the state has for enforcing building codes is a process that varies subnationally. This approach goes in line with \citet[103]{Snyder2001} who explains that subnational comparisons are useful to compare political and economic processes that vary spatially, and with \citet[286]{Ziblatt2008}, who points out that `any account, which attempts to explain local public goods provision \emph{without} reference to the capabilities of local government, might be incomplete.' I argue that when the landed elites were growing nationally but there were still important subnational clusters of industrial development, that meant a generalized situation of sectoral indeterminacy and contestation, positing credible sectoral threats to agricultural incumbents. These threats advanced sectoral alliances at the national level, in turn fostering institutional investments. Unlike \citet{Bahamonde:2017ab,Bahamonde:2017aa} who proxies sectoral contestation by looking at historical national sectoral outputs, in an effort to account for these subnational dynamics I model sectoral contestation by accounting for the sectoral composition of the subnational level.

The rest of the paper proceeds as follows. In \autoref{fiscal:sociology} I explain how the conflicting sectoral nature of the implementation of the income tax is linked to state capacities. Next, in \autoref{measurement} I introduce and explain the proposed measurement, and how it maps with state capacities. Then, in \autoref{models} I present some econometric evidence, and finally I offer some final comments in \autoref{discussion}. In \autoref{appendix} I show some Bayesian convergence diagnostics. 

\section{Fiscal Sociology, Sectoral Conflicts and Sate Consolidation\label{fiscal:sociology}}


% argument (2): fiscal system and sectoral conflicts \\ general
The expansion of the fiscal system has been traditionally associated with sectoral conflicts. For example, Schumpeter sees ``taxation in terms of group conflicts,''\footnote{\citet[14]{Monson2015}.} while others see taxation as ``an outcome of economic relations.''\footnote{Seligman (1895). In \citet[7]{Martin2009a}.} Following this tradition, I sketch a theory around the sectoral conflict that existed between the industrial and agricultural elites in Latin America. State centralization affects landowners and industrialists in different ways. Consequently, every sector has different preferences towards taxation and state centralization.\footnote{See \citet[289]{Acemoglu:1996rm} and \citet[50]{Best1976}.} On the one hand, as land fixity increases the risk premium of the landed elite's main asset,\footnote{\citet[512]{Robinson2006a}.} they systematically resisted taxation. On the other hand, as capital could be reinvested in nontaxable sectors, industrialists' preferences toward taxation were more elastic.\footnote{\citet[]{Hirschman:1970bl} and Ronald Rogowski in \citet[ch. 4]{Drake:1998pi}. However, see \citet[15]{Bates1985}.} However, class conflicts are more likely to resolve in favor of direct taxation when income inequality \emph{among the elite} is low.\footnote{\citet[157]{Tani1966} explains that the absence of ``wealth groups'' makes passing an income tax law easier.} When inequality among the elite is high, there are no incentives to cooperate, and rather elites rule in a monopolistic way. However, given that similar degrees of sectoral economic development can be converted into armies of similar capabilities,\footnote{\citet{Boix:2015aa}.} elites will have incentives to make agreements rather than engaging in conflict when their economic/military capacities are similar. In other words, when levels of inter-elite inequality are low, war is more likely to exhaust all existent assets without producing positive outcomes for either sector,\footnote{Richard Salvucci in \citet[48]{Uribe-Uran:2001aa}.} putting then pressures to reach agreements instead of engaging in armed conflicts. 


% argument (2): fiscal system and sectoral conflicts \\ Latin America
In the Latin American context, considering the initial institutional and economical advantages the agricultural sector enjoyed since colonial times, reducing inter-elite inequality meant the expansion of the industrial sector. The emergence of the industrial sector not only altered the structure of the economy but also the inter-sectoral balance of political power, accelerating the implementation of the income tax.\footnote{\citet{Bahamonde:2017ab}.} Critically, from the elite's perspective, it was in their interest to see these extractive capacities grow. Taxation is more likely to survive as an institution when it counts with the elite's `blessing.' \citet{Boix:1999tj} and \citet{Parente1994} explain how the development of certain institutions or the adoption of certain technologies are implemented when they go in the benefit of the elites. In fact, for the Latin American case, \citet{Beramendi2016} argue that ``capitalist elites [preferred] to shoulder a higher tax burden through progressive direct taxation, which they [viewed] as the least-worst economic option.''\footnote{They particularly argue that progressive taxation was better relative to ``trade taxation, which can negatively impact the industrial sector'' (p. 18).} This approach departs from the `fiscal contract' paradigm. As one proponent explains, economic `agents pay their taxes [...] when they enjoy corresponding benefits themselves.'\footnote{\citet[5]{Mahon2015}.} Instead, this  paper considers taxation as sectoral conflictual outcome. I agree with Martin et al. in that ``a tax is not a fee paid in direct exchange for a service, but rather an obligation to contribute,''\footnote{in \citet[3]{Martin2009a}.} and with \citet[71]{Best1976} in that ``taxes can be viewed as dependent upon the distribution of power rather than as an expression of the free choice of the majority of the people.'' 


% argument (3): sectoral conflicts and state capacities
A theory focused on sectoral conflicts offers also a theory of state consolidation. As others have argued, ``state formation will be more likely to the degree that powerful individual actors form two groups on the basis of divergent economic and political interests.''\footnote{\citet[1085]{Hechter1980a}.} The very implementation of the income tax produced a secular accumulation of know-how, particularly, of technologies able to monitor individual incomes. Observing individual economies and transforming private income into public property is what \emph{causes} state consolidation.\footnote{\citet[98]{Musgrave1992} and \citet[298]{Moore2004a}. While \citet{Kurtz2009,Kurtz:2013aa,Soifer2015a} situate the relevant state-building critical juncture at the end of the colonial period, before the class compromises I identify in this paper, I argue that the implementation of the income tax was an important building block in this process.} In fact, \citet[99]{Musgrave1992} argues that since taxation (specially of incomes) requires such a high degree of state penetration, public finances offer the key for a theory of state-building. Indirect taxes are, \emph{ceteris paribus}, easier to levy, and hence this kind of revenue is generally considered ``unearned income''\footnote{\citet[304]{Moore2004a}.} or ``easy-to-collect source of revenues.''\footnote{\citet[10]{Coatsworth2002}.} Given the relatively lower costs states have to incur to collect them, indirect taxes have a very low impact on state-building.\footnote{\citet[14]{Moore2004}.} For example \citet[46]{Krasner:1985lq} explains that ``tariffs and export taxes are easier to obtain than direct taxes, which require high levels of bureaucratic skill and voluntary compliance.'' In fact, when early Latin American states depended heavily on trade taxes, the state apparatus tended to be less developed.\footnote{\citet[177]{Campbell1993}.} Since customs administrations have always been concentrated in a few critical locations, especially ports, tariffs and customs duties did not require an elaborate fiscal structure.\footnote{\citet[132]{Bertola2012}.} Income taxation not only triggered other state capacities helping with the development of more skilled bureaucracies. Via a process of assimilation, it also helped to construct the figure of the \emph{citizen} centered around the concept of the \emph{taxpayer}. Regardless of an individual's race, religion, culture or any other kind of status, the state classifies its subjects according to their incomes and oblige them to pay, punishing whoever refuses to do so. From a sociological standpoint, this ``generality makes taxation a crucial element in the development of the `imagined community'\footnote{\citet[]{Anderson2006a}.} of the modern nation-state [...] Taxation enmeshes us in the web of generalized reciprocity that constitutes modern society.''\footnote{Martin et al. (in \citet[3]{Martin2009a}).}



