% chile
In all Latin American economies during and right after the colonial period, agriculture was the most important sector.\footnote{\citet[13]{Keller1931}.} And by extension, agricultural political elites were the most powerful elite.\footnote{\citet[45-46]{Wright1975}.} For the Chilean case in particular, \citet[106]{Collier:2002db} have argued that initially the ``national government was dominated by the central part of the country, with owners of large agricultural holdings playing a predominant role.''\footnote{Similarly, \citet[15]{McBride:1971fv} explains that ``Chile's people live on the soil. Her life is agricultural to the core. \emph{Her government has always been of farm owners. Her Congress is made up chiefly of rich landlords}. Social life is dominated by families whose proudest possession is the ancestral estate.'' Emphases are mine.} There existed an important asymmetry, however. While both the agricultural and industrial sectors were growing at the same pace (see \autoref{fig:incometax}, top panel), the latter were kept from participating in politics under fair conditions. This asymmetry led these two `antagonistic elites'\footnote{\citet[37-38]{Keller1931}.} to two bloody civil wars. \citet[23]{Zeitlin:1984aa} argues that the civil wars challenged a ``large landed property [elite against a] productive capital[ist] [elite].'' However, war was not sustainable over time. Given their relative similar degrees of economic development and military capacities, the two elites opted for a political compromise.\footnote{\citet{Geddes1991} argues that competition between two rival parties of about the same size creates clearer incentives to invest in political institutions.} In 1924, industrial elites accepted to be income taxed by agriculturalist incumbents in exchange of having a more open political system. The non-agricultural sector ``accepted taxation, \emph{while demanding state services and expecting to influence how tax revenues were spent}.''\footnote{Carmenza Gallo, in \citet[165]{Brautigam2008}. Emphases are mine.} In turn, the implementation of the income tax, as part of the sectoral bargain, was associated with the implementation of other state institutions, expanding the bureaucratic \emph{dominion} of the state. However, unlike other `regular' state institutions and services, taxing incomes in fact inflicted the state's coercive sovereignty unto the individual itself. \citet{Bahamonde:2017ac} finds that the expansion of the industrial sector in Chile leveraged industrial elites, accelerating the implementation of the income tax law. Importantly, the implementation of the income tax law was situated within a framework of sectoral conflicts and eventual concessions. For instance, the \emph{Servicio de Impuestos Internos} is among the finest tax institutions in Latin America. However, Guatemala imposed the income tax law very late, in 1963, and by 1967 the national income tax office employed 194 people, and only 9 of whom had graduated from college.\footnote{\citet[5]{DiJohn2006}.} While this case did implement the tax, this (potentially) state-\emph{making} institution was not situated during the formative period and consequently it did not reflect the early foundational sectoral economic cleavage. In this paper I show evidence that suggests that the implementation of the income tax in the presence of sectoral conflicts expanded Chilean state capacities. I also introduce a new measurement able to capture historical outcomes of state efforts.



\section{From Earthquake Death Tolls to State Capacities\label{measurement}}



% different measures
More than being blessed, the literature is in fact cursed with the over abundance of poor indicators of state capacities.\footnote{\citet[10]{Hanson2013b} compiled 24 different types of measurements of state-capacities, while \citet{Mata2009} constructed a combined measurement of 12 other indicators.} \citet[589]{Soifer2012} explains that there exists an ``industry of indices measuring state weakness, state failure, and state fragility [which] has cropped up in recent years.'' Yet, as \citet[347]{Fukuyama2013} explains, its abundance ``points to the poor state of empirical measures of the quality of states.'' The literature points out to two main concerns. First, `most fragility indices barely satisfy scientific standards.'\footnote{\citet[35]{Mata2009}. They point out particularly to the fact that data are usually poor or unavailable.} And second, most indices are conflated with analytical and conceptual problems.\footnote{I agree with \citet[586]{Soifer2012} in that most ``scholarship on state capacity [...] lack[s] a satisfying conceptualization and measurement scheme for this concept.'' See also \citet[1292]{Ferreira2017}.} One notable example is protection of the rule of law which is commonly used to proxy state capacities.\footnote{See for one example \citet[1237]{Besley2009}.} As \citet[543]{Kurtz2007} explain, this strategy is severely confounded ``with policy preferences over the structure of private property rights.'' On the one hand, this is problematic since the sources of these data are usually elite interviews. To ``the extent that public bureaucracies \emph{are} effective in imposing taxes or regulatory demands [...] they are likely to be judged `burdensome' and `growth-inhibiting' by many businesspersons,''\footnote{\citet[542]{Kurtz2007}. Emphasis in original.} introducing in this way systematic measurement error.\footnote{See also \citet[618]{Kurtz2012}.} Likewise, expert surveys suffer from the same problem.\footnote{\citet[349]{Fukuyama2013}.} On the other hand, the problem is conceptual. As \citet[247]{Soifer2008a} puts it, there is a widely spread ``problem of misalignment between dimension and indicator.'' \citet[619]{Kurtz2012} recommend to ``explicitly avoid an emphasis on outputs that are at the center of political or policy debates, such as property rights.'' For example, the U.S.S.R. did have a strong state, however it did not protect property rights. Another example has to do with the indicators provided by the World Bank. These series are ``[c]learly, the most comprehensive source for cross-national measures of governance.''\footnote{\citet[543]{Kurtz2007}.} One of the dimensions is the absence of violence. However, ``there isn't much byway of street crime or military coup attempts in North Korea,''\footnote{\citet[348]{Fukuyama2013}.} a state that can barely provide basic services to its population. Focusing on tax rates is not a solution either.\footnote{Yet, \citet[3]{Johnson2017} explain that `[t]ax revenue per capita is a commonly used metric of fiscal capacity,' which in turn might work as a proxy of state capacities. For example, \citet{Besley2014} adopt this strategy.} For example, in late imperial China, ``the high taxes on peasants [...] were the result of rulers' lack of power. Chinese rulers consistently attempted to limit official's excessive extractions from the masses, but were unable to do so.''\footnote{\citet[301]{Kiser1992}.}


% temporal
This paper identifies a third limitation. Besides of their conceptual and analytical problems, most measurements provide a rough approximation of \emph{contemporary} state capacities. Just to name a few examples, \citet[585]{Soifer2012} ``builds a new measure of state capacity for [...] contemporary Latin America [combining] multiple dimensions (extraction, security, and the administration of basic services).'' \citet[618-619]{Kurtz2012} propose an experimental design based on list-experiments\footnote{Refer to \citet[]{Aronow2014,Blair2012,Blair2014,Corstange2008,Corstange2010,Glynn2013,Imai2011,Imai2014a,Kane2004,KiewietDeJonge2015}.} to study (in an unbiased way) bureaucrat's opinions on whether ``the bureaucracy was really based on a competitive, meritocratic process; whether tenure protections are effective; whether extralegal payments or extortion take place,'' among others. Finally, \citet{Soifer2016a} employ a survey-based design to measure subnational state capacities. While these measurements overcome the problems mentioned above, they do not help us to study state capacities in a historical setup. Economic historians and students of political development have offered other measures that seek (or could potentially be used) to capture historical levels of state capacities, such as investments in public goods like infrastructure, roads,\footnote{See for example \citet{Mann1984a,Mann2008a,Acemoglu2005a,Saylor2012,Thies2009,Besley2010}.} electrification (measured as light intensity per pixel),\footnote{\citet{Huntington2014}.} and railroads.\footnote{\citet[302]{Saylor2012} and \citet{Coatsworth1974a}.} However, many of these measurement are debatable. For example, \citet[593]{Soifer2012} explains that ``railroads were often constructed by private actors.''\footnote{Footnote \#11.} The same problem applies to other types of infrastructures. The are others more appropriated strategies such as the opening of postal offices,\footnote{See for example \citet{Robinson2016}.} the administration of national censuses\footnote{See for example \citet{Soifer2013a} and \citet{Centeno:2002qf}. This technique is borrowed from demographers, and it compares the age structure (incorrectly) captured in the census with the an assumed `right' theoretical age distribution. Low-capacity states should inaccurately round ages or inflate certain intervals, producing error. This error is usually computed in the Whipple's index which serves as a proxy for state capacities.} and vaccination.\footnote{\citet{Soifer2012}.} While these measurements advance our knowledge on \emph{historical} state capacities, there are still other problems. Censuses for example provide a \emph{non-continuous temporal measurement} of state capacities. For instance, censuses are applied in Chile every ten years. Having just a few snapshots of state-capacity should compromise any statistical analysis. In turn, vaccines are usually targeted to primary and high school students. In practice, vaccines are administered by the schools themselves, both public and private. Private schools might be more efficient in doing do, inflating the \emph{average} level of state-capacity. 



%Others have used economic growth,\footnote{\citet{Fearon2003} and \citet{Besley:2011aa}.}\todo{Mahoney?} which is also problematic.\todo{explain why}


% my measurement
To solve some of these limitations, I propose earthquake death tolls as an alternative measurement of historical state capacities. Unlike censuses, unfortunately, earthquakes happen very often. Yet, they are not well studied in the discipline. While ``[e]arthquakes alone claim thousands of lives a year,''\footnote{\citet[1908]{Anbarci2005}.} ``[d]isasters are not as well studied [...] in the field of political science.''\footnote{\citet[719]{Brancati2007}.} Building on \citet[113]{Mann1984a}, the proposed measurement captures state's `infrastructural' power.\footnote{He defines infrastructural power as  ``the capacity of the state [to] actually [...] penetrate civil society, and to implement logistically political decisions throughout the realm.''} ``Natural hazards can be seen as a function of a specific natural process and human [...] activity.''\footnote{\citet[627]{Raschky2008}.} Given that earthquakes happen at random and are completely exogenous to the affected locality,\footnote{\citet[728]{Brancati2007} explains that ``earthquakes constitute a natural experiment.'' \citet[27]{Gignoux2016} also point out ``that the occurrence of earthquakes can be viewed as random [allowing the analyses of] these events as a set of repeated social experiments.'' \citet[32, unpublished]{Caruso2017} also ``[exploits] the exogenous variation in the location and timing of natural disasters, as well as the exposure of different cohorts to the shock.''} the only part that is left unexplained is the systematic human component, which is what the measurement captures. Earthquakes are orthogonal to levels of state and economic development development,\footnote{\citet[271]{Kahn2005} and \citet{Brancati2007}.} and by extension, they happen at any level of state capacity. Consequently, keeping earthquake magnitudes constant, (weighted) death counts should be attributed to the (in)capacity of the states to invest in preparedness and mitigation institutions.\footnote{To make sure, while ``earthquakes may not be preventable, it is possible to prevent the disasters they cause'' (\citet[209]{Escaleras2007}). Similarly, \citet[1911]{Anbarci2005} explain that ``the potentially devastating effects of major earthquakes are, if not preventable, at least subject to significant mitigation.'' For a similar approach, see \citet[130]{Noji:1996aa}.} I focus on earthquakes and not on other natural disasters such as `extreme temperature events, floods, landslides, and windstorms'\footnote{\citet[280]{Kahn2005}.} because earthquakes cannot be foreseen, and such, they put to a test the capacity of the states to have their preventive institutions \emph{already} in place and in good shape. State capacities consist of sustained \emph{proactive} efforts of enforcing institutions throughout the territory, and hence short-term \emph{reactive} actions should \emph{not} be considered state-\emph{making}.\footnote{In other words, other ``natural disasters can be foreseen (or predicted with some probability) and thus measures can be taken to limit their severity'' (\citet[1908]{Anbarci2005}).} Moreover, unlike other natural disasters, earthquakes do not allow actors to adapt their behavior while the quake is happening. For example, in the case of famines, the institutions of ``calamity relief in India [...] emphasize the need for local administrators to look for \emph{signs}, such as large drops in food production and increases in food prices, which \emph{signal} an impending crisis.''\footnote{\citet[1423]{Besley2002}. Emphases are mine. In fact, as \citet[273]{Kahn2005} points out to the very non-significant low correlation between predictable and unpredictable natural disasters.} In fact, \citet[716]{Brancati2007} explains that ``[e]arthquakes may provoke conflict more than any other type of natural disaster \emph{because} they have rapid onsets [and] are not predictable.''\footnote{Emphasis is mine.} 


% preparedeness // construction
The capacity states have of deploying inspectors throughout the territory to enforce quake-sensitive zoning and building codes is a reflexion of the overall levels of a country's state capacity. Since ``[e]arthquake-resistant construction depends on responsible governance,''\footnote{\citet[153]{Ambraseys2011}. Similarly, \citet[628]{Raschky2008} argue that ``the effects of natural hazards [do] not solely depend on a region's topographic or climatic exposure to natural processes [...] but [on] the region's \emph{institutional} vulnerability.'' Emphasis is mine.} state capacities act as a scope condition, particularly, undermining or permitting the \emph{implementation} of these norms. For example, \citet[169]{Bilham2013} explains that ``although engineering codes may \emph{exist} [,] mechanisms to \emph{implement} these codes are largely unavailable''\footnote{Emphases are mine.} in low-capacity states. For example, \citet[1910]{Anbarci2005} explain that ``while Iran has building codes which are comparable to those existing in the United States, they tend to be enforced only in the country's larger cities,'' failing to monitor the countryside, which was where most of the deaths occurred in the 6.4 earthquake in Changureh in 2002.\footnote{Similarly, \citet[865]{Bardhan2016} explains that ``unlike in the case of some macroeconomic policies, [...] the effectiveness of the state varies enormously across localities and administrative levels within the same country.''} The proposed measurement bridges this gap by incorporating and modeling the state's effort of enforcing these codes at the subnational level. Critically, ``[e]arthquake-resistant features are costly to verify after construction is complete [...] Steel reinforcement bars make a well-known contribution to earthquake resistance in concrete buildings[,] not only is the steel itself invisible [...] but the durability of the steel depends on the quality and quantity of concrete around it.''\footnote{\citet[1531]{Keefer2011}.} This is the so called `cover-up' concept: ``inappropriate foundations can be hidden beneath walls, shoddily assembled steel work can be hidden beneath concrete [and] poorly mixed concrete can be hidden behind paint.''\footnote{\citet[167]{Bilham2013}.} 

Only states with higher capacities overcome their logistic limitations and successfully implement and enforce these regulations at the local level. The Chilean government started its efforts to ameliorate the impact of earthquakes after the great quake of 1928 in Talca. A first effort happened in 1929 when \href{http://www.leychile.cl/Navegar?idNorma=149306}{\emph{Ley} number 4563} was implemented. The law was among the first attempts to regulate ``construction, reconstruction or any other repairing or transformations [...] without a permit from the authorities.'' Importantly, the law required that all blueprints had to be signed by an expert before the construction started. By 1930, \href{https://www.leychile.cl/Navegar?idNorma=1038437&idParte=0&idVersion=}{\emph{Decreto} number 4882} was adopted, but this time the rule made a number of technical prescriptions,\footnote{See specially article 151.} determining what kinds of construction materials ought to be used, among other requirements. Critically, while the central government had retained the control of the supervision of the code since the promulgation of the \emph{ley}, the \emph{decreto} explicitly created the figure of the \emph{inspector} to supervise, enforce and monitor these measures at the local level. Furthermore, \emph{art\'iculo} 414 of the Chilean \emph{Decreto} 4882 granted \emph{inspectores} `free access to the building' at any time during the construction process. My measurement picks up whether these good intentions written in paper actually scored lower death tolls when shocked by the average earthquake.\footnote{Thus, my measurement captures state outcomes. \citet{Fukuyama2013} is very critical of `outcome-oriented' measurements. However, this outcome is different. Unlike the proportion of tax over GDP which could end up being wasted (p. 353), or ``educational outcomes [which depend] much more strongly on factors like friends and family'' (p. 355), death tolls associated to earthquakes are \emph{not} `hard to measure' (p. 356) neither they are subject to `normative' concerns. I also disagree in that `econometric techniques' to control for these and other factors add `another layer of complexity.' Similarly, \citet[619]{Kurtz2012} explain that the ``problem [...] with output based measures is that they necessarily include information on policy choice.'' However, it would be hard to say that people's lives are subject to `ideological' or `policy preferences.'}



% basic social contract
Properly enforced and implemented building codes, among other mitigation measures, not only save lives. These kinds of institutions embody the most basic form of social contract that exists between the state and its subjects. The collapse of commerce buildings and private houses trigger higher levels of looting and social unrest. States are interested in preventing looting and social unrest because elected officials, as the visible faces of \emph{the} state, care not only about their electoral survival (or just `survival' in the case of unelected officials), but also about the legitimacy of the whole apparatus. That is, in the event of social unrest, not only the essential social Hobbesian-like contract is broken but also the expectations for social peace and the ability of the state to monopolize physical violence are questioned.\footnote{Others have studied how in some context earthquakes damage interpersonal trust. For example, \citet[419]{Carlin2014a} argue that ``state capacity plays a decisive role in determining natural disasters' consequences for social capital.''} The physical presence of the state literally crumbles when institutions of social coercion and discipline such as state schools, prisons and police stations, collapse. For example, when the 7.0 earthquake hit Hati in 2010, the \emph{Prison Civile de Port-au-Prince} had a population of 4,500 inmates. During the quake, five inmates died. As a prison guard describes it, \emph{everyone escaped. Everyone. Except the dead.} This natural disaster exacerbated the already existent chaos, freeing ``gang bosses, kidnappers, gunmen,'' among others.\footnote{\citet{Reed:2011}. See also \citet{Laursen2010}.} Critically, under these circumstances, the legitimacy of the state, and particularly, the \emph{tax state}, reduces to zero. Thus, officials (elected or not), care about the potentially negative outcomes the lack of building code enforcement might cause. For humanitarian or selfish reasons, it is in their best interest to make sure that these institutions are enforced throughout the territory. Should the state fail, its extractive enterprise will be the first one in being scrutinized.


% advantages // it's objective and subnational
This measurement has a number of advantages. Unlike survey-based or policy-based measures, earthquake death tolls are an \emph{objective} measurement of earthquake preparedness,\footnote{That is, ``it does not rely on an effort to measure the beliefs of citizens about the nature of the state, the legitimacy of its leaders or the institutional procedures that selected them, or even perceptions of the efficiency of public bureaucracies'' (\citet[616]{Kurtz2012}).} an activity that \emph{any} state \emph{must} perform.\footnote{I agree with \citet[619]{Kurtz2012} in that  an ``output-linked approach [...] should only examine public sector outputs that are not particularly politicized, and generally perceived to be essential state functions across a very broad set of states.'' In fact, he mentions building codes as one possibility. Similarly, \citet[422]{Carlin2014a} explain that ``a basket of `minimal' state functions [typically includes] primary education, public health, rule of law, public finance management, and disaster relief.''} \citet[58]{Kurtz:2013aa} for example explains that ``the best measures [of state capacities] would be of the sorts of activities that all (or nearly all) states consider to be of primary importance.'' Additionally, \citet[235-236]{Soifer2008a} divides the state infrastructural power in three layers, `national capabilities,'\footnote{This layer `sees state infrastructural power as a characteristic of the central state'.} the `weight of the state'\footnote{This relates to `how the exercise of state power shapes the society it controls.'} and a `subnational' component which tracks ``the ability of the state to exercise control within its territory.'' Earthquake death tolls (as a measurement of state capacities) maps well into the first and third components. Since death tolls are a function of how well/bad building codes are \emph{enforced} by the state \emph{throughout the territory}, state-capacities is not a nationally uniform process, making a subnational approach more appropriated. 


% This measurement has a number of drawbacks
This measurement has a number of drawbacks, however. Obviously, the country needs to have earthquakes, possibly limiting the number of potential cases. However, most ``earthquakes occur at the various borders of the Pacific plate, the Western border of the Latin American plate, and the boundaries between the African, the Arabic and the Indian plates and the Eurasian plate,'' allowing potential cross-country comparisons within most of the developing world.\footnote{\citet[1534]{Keefer2011}. From a population size perspective, this measurement is also convenient. A ``quarter of the world's population inhabits [...] the northern edge of the Arabian and Indian Plates that are colliding with the southern margin of the Eurasian Plate'' (\citet[618]{Bilham2013a}). Finally, other measurements also are contingent on the context. For example, \citet[593]{Soifer2012} proposes a measurement of administrative capacities focusing on how states are able to enforce voter registration `where voting is mandatory.' This strategy evidently shortens the sample to only democratic countries, introducing potential sample selection biases.} Moreover, there are countries, like India or the United States, where earthquakes happen in certain regions only. Presumably, mitigation policies in these place would need to be targeted to specific areas, possibly undermining the assumption that the these kinds of policies should penetrate the `entire' territory.\footnote{\citet[164]{Dunbar2003} explains that the Indian state implements targeted policies (that might not necessarily correspond to the administrative areas) based on isoseismal maps that define different zones of seismic hazard.} Another potential concern is that the ability of counting the death-toll might be a function of state capacities itself.\footnote{If this were true, states with higher capacities would have higher death tolls, while states with lower capacities, due to their incapacity to count, lower death tolls.} However, civic organizations, the Catholic Church, and particularly, the press (national and local) have been the main entities who willingly or not have carried out the task of enumerating casualties. Another potential issue has to do with the measurement of the magnitudes. Before the instrumental period, magnitudes were obtained in an estimative way. And while there are methods to approximate historical felt magnitudes to instrumental-like intensities,\footnote{\citet{Szeliga2010}.} this unfortunately adds more than one layer of complexity. All in all, this measurement offers a rough approximation of historical state capacities. And while some econometric techniques might ameliorate some of the problems, it is unlikely that they disappear completely.



