% explain dataset
I constructed a novel dataset using the \emph{Significant Earthquake Database} compiled by the National Centers for Environmental Information (NOAA) as a starting point.\footnote{\citet[]{noaa2015}.} The dataset `contains information on destructive earthquakes from 2150 B.C. to the present,' and records the number of deaths,\footnote{Importantly, the NOAA distinguishes earthquake deaths from total deaths (which includes tsunami casualties). I use the former.} the magnitude and year, and the latitude and longitude of every quake, among other information. Using archival census data from 1907 to 2012,\footnote{Particularly, censuses of 1907, 1920, 1930, 1940, 1952, 1960, 1970, 1982, 1992, 2002 and 2012. Some of them were kept at the \emph{Biblioteca Nacional} and others at the \emph{National Statistic Institute} historical library.} I complemented the NOAA dataset with local population at the municipal level where the quake hit. This way I am able to weight the death toll by local population.\footnote{I use population to weight the number of casualties, not take the proportion of casualties. While in most occasions I was able to recover the actual population, in some instances that was not possible. In these cases, I take the population of the most concentrated area nearby. Consequently, I adopted a more general approach, and used the population variable as a proxy.} Using archival census data as well, I also considered the main economic activity of the affected municipality,\footnote{Agricultural, industrial, or mixed (i.e., both agricultural and industrial).} and also whether the affected locality was urban or rural.\footnote{If more than 50\% of the population lives in an urban setting, I assigned a 1 to that municipality, 0 otherwise. Urban concentrations are more likely to have vertical constructions rather than one-story buildings, increasing the potential number of casualties. I thank Daniel Kelemen for this suggestion.} The death tolls and magnitudes proportionated by the NOAA dataset were contrasted case by case with historical press archival information.\footnote{\emph{El Mercurio} and \emph{La Naci\'on} newspapers, both kept at the \emph{Archivo} of the \emph{Biblioteca Nacional de Chile}.} Magnitudes in particular were also compared with the \href{http://www.isc.ac.uk/iscbulletin/search/bulletin/}{International Seismological Centre}. All these are subnational-level variables. Next, I included national-level indicators that aim to proxy sectoral conflicts at the national level. Following \citet{Bahamonde:2017ab} and \citet{Bahamonde:2017aa}, I proxy national sectoral competition and specifically the degree in which the industrial elites challenged incumbent landowners, calculating the proportion of agricultural growth relative to industrial growth as presented in the  \href{http://moxlad-staging.herokuapp.com/home/en?}{MOxLAD} data (see \autoref{fig:incometax}, bottom panel).\footnote{``These data build on the studies and statistical abstracts of the Economic Commission for Latin America, but also rely on Mitchell's International Historical Statistics, International Monetary Fund's International Financial Statistics, the World Bank's World Development Indicators and a variety of national sources.'' I used the \emph{agriculture value-added} and \emph{manufacturing value-added} variables. The former measures ``the output of the sector net of intermediate inputs and includes the cultivation of crops, livestock production, hunting, forestry and fishing.'' The later  ``[r]eports the output of the sector net of intermediate inputs.'' Both of them are expressed in local currency at 1970 constant prices.} According to \citet[790]{Astorga2005}, these data provide extended comparable sectoral value-added series in constant purchasing power parity prices. Even when pre-1900 earthquakes are recorded in both the NOAA data and my own dataset (\autoref{fig:earthquake:ts:plot:chile}), the economic data provided by MOxLAD limits the scope of this paper from $\Sexpr{min(datsc$year)}$ to $\Sexpr{max(datsc$year)}$ (\autoref{fig:incometax}).



% case justification
Chile is a good case to study infrastructural state-capacities using this earthquake dataset since it has considerable variance regarding quake magnitudes and locations. \autoref{fig:earthquake:ts:plot:chile} plots the earthquakes, the years and the magnitudes, while \autoref{fig:earthquake:map:plot:chile} plots the geographical distribution and magnitudes of the quakes. Both plots consider the full sample starting in $\Sexpr{min(dat.chile$year)}$ and ending in $\Sexpr{max(dat.chile$year)}$. The northern part of Chile has historically been an industrial region, while the southern part of Chile has traditionally been an agricultural region. Relatedly, both regions vary according to their climate as well. Chile is arid in the north, limiting agricultural activity, but it has a temperate oceanic climate in the south, a more appropriated climate for agriculture. Also, distance from Santiago, the capital city located in the middle (around latitude 33$^{\circ}$), might impose some degree of difficulty for the central government to reach out the farthest northern/southern parts of the territory. All in all, given that earthquakes happen at various latitudes and in different magnitudes, both regions have been exposed indistinctly to a wide range of shocks. There is also variance considering longitude. Closeness to the Andean mountains (around longitude 70$^{\circ}$) determines the ruggedness of the terrain, presumably making it harder for the state to penetrate these areas.\footnote{Moreover, \citet[729]{Brancati2007} explains that ``[e]arthquakes often occur in mountainous areas.''} However shocks have affected the territory from coast to mountain.\footnote{Since ``most of the damage in major earthquakes occurs within 30 km of the epicenter,'' (\citet[172]{Dunbar2003}) I don't necessarily drop quakes that didn't happen on land. While the epicenter might have happened a few miles away from the shore, the consequences certainly reached the land.} In sum, quakes have shocked the country as a whole regardless of longitude and latitude, distance from the center, type of climate and main economic activity. 



