% Poisson model // main IVs
The unit of analysis is the earthquake.\footnote{\citet[273]{Kahn2005} also considers that ``the unit of analysis is [the] disaster.''} As an event, each earthquake has a death toll, a subnational location identified by its latitude and longitude, a magnitude, a main economic activity of the locality where the quake hit, a local population, and an urban/rural setting. All these factors are subnational. At the national level, I consider sectoral outputs (as a proportion), population, year, and a dummy variable indicating whether in a given year the income tax was adopted. Specifically, using a Bayesian Poisson regression,\footnote{\citet[1907]{Anbarci2005} use ``a Negative Binomial estimation strategy with both random and fixed estimators'' to estimate death tolls, \citet[276]{Kahn2005} estimates a Zero Inflated Negative Binomial model, \citet[729]{Brancati2007} uses ``a negative binomial model with robust standard errors clustered by country,'' and \citet{Escaleras2007} use ``a Negative Binomial specification.'' Yet, no study tests for over dispersion. In my dataset I do not find evidence for that, hence I employ a Poisson model.} I model the count of dead individuals caused by earthquakes. The main independent variable is the interaction between the proportion of national agriculture output relative to national industrial output (one slope per economic activity at the local level) and a dummy variable which indicates whether by year $t$ the income tax law had been implemented (see \autoref{fig:incometax}, bottom panel). This strategy is relevant since I am interested in whether the implementation of the income tax was implemented in a context of national sectoral contestation. In turn, sectoral slopes model subnational sources of sectoral contestation. I also included year fixed-effects to account for time-varying confounding factors.\footnote{\citet[729]{Brancati2007} also includes in his analyses ``year-fixed effects to control for trends over time.''} For instance, fiscal development could be a function of country-specific prior state-building capacities. Fixed-effects should be able to account for this and other unmeasured yearly factors such as the evolution of the political system, demographic, climate and cultural changes as well as economic shocks (both national and international). I also included latitude to control for the proximity to the Andean mountains. This variable controls for a built-in tectonic predisposition to earthquakes, and longitude to control for climate and other unmeasured conditions that make agricultural development more difficult. In turn, both measurements serve as good proxies of terrain ruggedness and the difficulties of the state in reaching these parts of the country.\footnote{Undoubtedly, there are many more factors that might increase the death tolls. \citet[154]{Ambraseys2011} for example explain that the ``number of fatalities depends on whether an earthquake happens at night or during the day, in the winter or in the summer, in a mountainous region or in a valley, after strong and protracted fore-shocks and with or without warning.'' While in my model some of these factors are accounted for, I do not have complete data on the hour of the shock. However, \citet[1309]{Lomnitz1970} explains that ``some of the larger Chilean earthquakes which have caused deaths'' between the 1900's and the 1960's have been afternoon quakes. See specially Table 1 in p. 1310. Other factors such as ``the speed of tectonic movements [and] the degree to which the lower plate bends the upper plate'' and the focal depth (\citet[1534]{Keefer2011}) could not be included due to the lack of complete historical data. However, the year fixed effects could pick up at some extent these unmeasured components.} More formally, I fit the next equation,





\begin{equation} \label{model:1}
\begin{split}
\text{Deaths} \;\sim\; & \text{Poisson}(\lambda_{i})\\
log(\lambda_{i})  = 
& \mu + \beta_{1_j}\text{Proportion}_{i} + \beta_{2}\text{Tax}_{i} + 
\beta_{3_j}\text{Proportion}_{i}\times\text{Tax}_{i} +
\beta_{4_j}\text{Magnitude}_{i} + \\
& \beta_{5}\text{Population}_{i} + \beta_{6}\text{Urban}_{i} + \beta_{7}\text{Latitude}_{i} + 
\beta_{8}\text{Longitude}_{i} + \beta_{9_t}\text{Year}_{i}
\end{split}
\end{equation}

where,

\begin{equation*} \label{indexes:1}
\begin{split}
i_{1,...I} & \; \text{where} \; \text{I}=\Sexpr{N}\\
j_{1,...J} & \; \text{where} \; \text{J}=\Sexpr{NSector}\\
t_{1,...T} & \; \text{where} \; \text{T}=\Sexpr{yearN},
\end{split}
\end{equation*}


% multilevel // other variables // econometrics
and the $i$ subscript denotes the unit of analysis (i.e. earthquake),\footnote{\citet[278]{Kahn2005} follows the same strategy.} the $j$ index expresses the type of subnational economic composition of the affected locality (agricultural, industrial, or mixed), and the $t$ subscripts denotes the year when earthquake $i$ happened. Finally, $\mu$ is the intercept.  

Since the `treatment,' i.e. sources of sectoral contestation, occur simultaneously at the national and subnational levels, I implement a multilevel model.\footnote{\citet[237]{Gelman:2006bh}. I do not claim in any way this is a causal method.} While the proportion of agricultural/industrial outputs and the implementation of the income tax take place at the national level, there exists a secular tendency of economic regional clusters to expand despite national sectoral growth aggregates. I conceptualize this tendency as a source of subnational sectoral contestation. For instance, when \emph{national} agricultural output is faster than industrial growth, but industrialists are the most advantaged elite at the \emph{subnational} level, it speaks to a generalized situation of sectoral indeterminacy and contestation, where the landowning class is not completely the dominant elites. In this example, the emergence of these clusters are also signals of the secular relative declining of the agricultural sector. Higher levels of sectoral contestation translated into more credible threats, advancing sectoral alliances at the national level, fostering institutional investments. 

The multilevel component of \autoref{model:1} allows the slopes of the national proportion of agriculture relative to industry ($\beta_{1_j}$) and the earthquake's magnitude ($\beta_{4_j}$) to vary by the $j$th dominant subnational sector. Since earthquakes can happen more than once per year, in my dataset $i > t$.\footnote{For the years in which there is just one earthquake, the `group' variable has only one observation. This does not endangers the robustness of the model. \citet[276]{Gelman:2006bh} explain that it ``is even acceptable to have one observation in many of the groups.''} The estimated parameters $\beta_{k}$ have noninformative normally distributed priors,\footnote{``Noninformative prior distributions are intended to allow Bayesian inference for parameters about which not much is known beyond the data included in the analysis at hand'' (\citet[520]{Gelman2006}).} while precisions $\tau_{p}$ of $\beta_{(1,3)_j}$, $\beta_{4_j}$ and $\beta_{9_t}$ have noninformative Gamma priors. More formally, I considered the following:

\begin{equation*} \label{indexes:2}
\begin{split}
\beta_{k,...K} \;\sim\; & \mathcal{N}(0, 0.01) \; \text{where} \; \text{K}=9\\
\tau_{p,...P} \;\sim\; & \mathcal{G}(0.5, 0.001) \; \text{where} \; \text{P}=3.
\end{split}
\end{equation*}



% explain table and justify main variables
Developed states should be able to supervise quake-resistant construction practices, lowering death-tolls of the average earthquake. \emph{Do higher levels of sectoral contestation translate into state development?} In this paper I concentrate on the state-\emph{building} effects of the income tax law. When the tax was implemented under contexts of sectoral contestation, a series of inter-elite reforms crystallized a new institutional order, replacing the old one inherited since colonial times. \autoref{regression:table} shows the posterior predictive distributions of the multi-level Poisson regression, particularly, the predicted death counts conditional on observed covariates. The main quantity of interest is $\beta_{3_j}$, the coefficient on the interaction between the national proportion of $\frac{\text{Agriculture}}{\text{Industry}}$ and the implementation of the income tax law. Given the initial advantage of the landed elites, a higher proportion means lower levels of sectoral contestation, while a lower proportion means higher contestation levels. In turn, to model subnational sources of sectoral contestation, the coefficient is indexed by $j$, the sectoral composition of the average subnational unit. \citet{Brambor2005} explain that constitutive terms ($\beta_{1_j}$ and $\beta_{2}$) should not be interpreted, while \citet{Ai2003} explain the coefficient of the interaction term ($\beta_{3_j}$) should not be interpreted either. Following their advice, I computed and plotted the conditional effect of the implementation of the income tax law under different contexts of sectoral competition. \autoref{fig:interaction:plots:run} shows that when the income tax is implemented under non-competitive circumstances, the state has less capacities enforcing building codes, increasing its vulnerability to earthquakes (and increasing the death-toll). As argued above, only when the tax is implemented under contexts of sectoral contestation this institution will be more likely to have state-\emph{making} capacities. In particular, the analyses show that as the relative size of agriculture increases, the income tax \emph{rises} the death toll within a $\Sexpr{abs(round(max(agr.plot$mean[agr.plot$Tax=="Yes" & agr.plot$prop.range==min(agr.plot$prop.range)])))}$-$\Sexpr{abs(round(max(agr.plot$mean[agr.plot$Tax=="Yes" & agr.plot$prop.range==max(agr.plot$prop.range)])))}$ range when the average subnational affected locality is \emph{also} agricultural (lower contestation). However, the income tax law \emph{decreases} the death-toll within a $\Sexpr{abs(round(max(ind.plot$mean[ind.plot$Tax=="Yes" & ind.plot$prop.range==min(ind.plot$prop.range)])))}$-$\Sexpr{abs(round(max(ind.plot$mean[ind.plot$Tax=="Yes" & ind.plot$prop.range==max(ind.plot$prop.range)])))}$ range when the average subnational affected locality is industrial (higher contestation).



