Substantively, the income tax law expanded the overall Chilean state capacities. Critically, the tax was not important because of the new revenue it collected. While Humud (1969, p. 154) explains that the income tax generated considerable resources for the Chilean treasury,\footnote{\citet[451-452]{Bowman1982}.} I contend that the tax was important for state-making because its implementation required a series of sectoral compromises, triggering a series of other institutional investments, such as the implementation of checks-and-balances (to monitor tax spending) and the development of skilled bureaucracies. Hence, in years when the tax had been implemented, the state was better equipped with these state resources to confront earthquakes in a better way. And while public economists usually focus on tax revenues, I depart from this strategy. Higher revenues do not mean higher stateness levels. For example, since American institutions were deliberately designed to limit the exercise of state power, the U.S. taxes very little.\footnote{\citet[6]{Fukuyama:2004nr}.} However, it is not reasonable to say that the U.S. has a `weak state.' To summarize, sectoral contestation conceptualized as rapid national agricultural growth \emph{and} rapid subnational industrial growth, and the implementation of the income tax are positively associated with increasing levels of state capacities. 


All that said, it is important to rule out the possibility that both industrial \emph{and} agricultural localities are shocked by earthquakes in the same fashion. Otherwise, there might be an endogeneity problem: sectors would be self selecting themselves into more/less earthquake-prone zones. \autoref{regression:table} shows the posterior means of magnitudes by agricultural, industrial and mixed localities. Overall, there does not seem to be substantive evidence to suggest that this is the case. In \autoref{appendix} I present a number of graphical evidence to suggest good fit and convergence of the model. Additional diagnostic plots are available \href{https://github.com/hbahamonde/Earthquake_Paper/raw/master/Bahamonde_Earthquake_Paper_Diagnostic_Plots.pdf}{\texttt{here}}. Overall, the model is robust and convergence is good.


\section{Final Comments\label{discussion}}

I theorized that when the income tax was implemented under politically contested circumstances, this institution expanded the overall state capacities, crystallizing a series of reforms that replaced the old institutional order inherited since colonial times. In turn, the econometric analyses suggest that industrial expansion (in the form of political contestation) is associated with lower death-tolls. These results combined speak to a general theory of state-capacities and how they can be traced to inter-sectoral conflicts and compromises. While the lack of an economic challenger prevents political contestation, the secular emergence of industrial economic clusters leverages industrialist elites, giving them more bargaining power. The Chilean case suggested that industrial elites accepted to be income taxed in exchange of being allowed to participate in politics under fairer conditions. Importantly, all these elite compromises took place during the formative years of the Chilean state and during a period of structural indetermination, where no elite had a clear economic/military/political advantage, locking the Chilean state within a path of development. 

Particularly, I leveraged the fiscal sociology theory, explaining how the implementation of the tax gave the state via `learning by doing' the necessary know-how to penetrate individual economies. In turn, the \emph{praxis} of converting private income into public property gave the \emph{tax state} the capacity to enforce other institutions throughout the territory. That is, the capacity the state had of taxing its subjects \emph{diffused} to other state institutions via spillovers. In this paper I identify one such institution, building codes and construction regulations.

The paper also introduced a novel earthquake dataset where I leveraged the exogeneity of earthquakes to capture how the Chilean state has been able to enforce a number of regulations that seek to norm the construction and infrastructure sectors. The capacity the state has to enforce these institutions at the local level is in fact a projection of its \emph{overall} state capacities. This measurement is neutral to other issues related to policy preferences (such as protection of property rights), and hence protecting the population from earthquakes is an activity that \emph{all} states should pursue. The measurement is not confounded with levels of economic growth or type of regime either. It would be hard to think of a state with high capacities that is unable to enforce construction codes at the local level. Not only democratic leaders should care about this essential state activity, but dictators too. Regardless of the type of legitimacy any leader has, \emph{all} leaders levy taxes. Should the state fail to norm the construction of infrastructure, earthquakes will cause higher levels of looting and instability. Under these circumstances the state's taxing endeavors will be the first to fall. The measurement has a number of limitations. However, it serves as a good proxy for state capacities. Future research should apply this measurement to other countries, and if possible, with a larger time span. 

